* Tamlin Pavelsky (http://uncglobalhydrology.org/)
** Can we observe river widths directly?
** Global river widths from satellite - this is useful for surface area (e.g. flood extent) and hydrodynamic modelling
** First effort was successful for large water bodies but not good at smaller streams
** River networks are fractal (i.e. they are formed through the repetition of the same process)
*** This can be used to extrapolate river widths which are too narrow to be detected through remote sensing
** Validation of method through field work - measuring river width every 5m along a stream
** Data being used:
*** Landsat (~30m)
*** Planet Lab (https://www.planet.com/markets/education-and-research/) (~2-3m)
** Papers cited:
*** Allen et al 2018, Similarity of stream width distributions across headwater systems, Nature Communications
*** Allen et al 2018, Global extent of rivers and streams, Science
*** Barefoot et al, in review,  Temporally Variable Stream Width and Surface Area Distributions in a Headwater Catchment, WRR
** Software available
*** RivWidth - http://uncglobalhydrology.org/rivwidth/
*** RivWidthCloud - not currently available on that website, but may be available upon request
** Some interesting questions (of mine):
*** How well does the method perform in mountainous catchments?
*** Could we use machine-learning (e.g. Random Forest) to estimate additional features of the channel geometry? Consider different typologies - triangle, trapezium, each with a set of parameters which could be estimated based on auxillary remote sensing data + observations.
*** Combine with LIDAR data -> streamflow

